#---
# purpose: "Enumerable.reduce/3 suspend returns a real resumable closure at the runtime-value boundary"
# paths: [fz2-run, fz2-interp, fz2-build]
#---
#
# # enum_reduce_suspend
#
# Pins the materialization boundary for `Enumerable.reduce_list/3` suspend:
#
# ```fz
# Enumerable.reduce(xs, {:suspend, 0}, fn (x, acc) -> {:cont, acc + x})
# ```
#
# The suspend clause returns `{:suspended, acc, fn () -> ... end}`. That closure
# is a source value, not an internal native continuation edge, so it must remain a
# real heap closure even as native call continuations become direct or lazy.
#
# Target for native JIT/AOT:
#
# - the three-element input list allocates three cons cells;
# - the returned suspend function allocates one closure;
# - the current native path also boxes one scalar before the suspend boundary;
# - `closure_allocs = 1`;
# - `closure_bytes = 48`;
# - `scalar_box_allocs = 1`;
# - `scalar_box_bytes = 16`.
#
# Interpreter / REPL note:
#
# - the suspended continuation still remains a real heap closure with the same
#   allocation profile as before;
# - the rendered function identity is currently `#fn<3/3>` rather than
#   `#fn<4/3>`, which is numbering drift in the printer rather than a semantic
#   change in the suspend boundary.
fn main() do
  xs = [1, 2, 3]
  out = Enumerable.reduce(xs, {:suspend, 0}, fn (x, acc) -> {:cont, acc + x} end)

  dbg(out)
  stats = Process.heap_alloc_stats()
  dbg({
    stats[:list_cons_allocs],
    stats[:list_cons_bytes],
    stats[:struct_allocs],
    stats[:struct_bytes],
    stats[:closure_allocs],
    stats[:closure_bytes],
    stats[:scalar_box_allocs],
    stats[:scalar_box_bytes]
  })
end
